Even if we help just one woman make the switch, it’s a victory. It’s about more than just a product; it’s about comfort, confidence, and breaking the silence around menstruation.

You can’t always be there to protect her❤️‍🩹
.
Every year, Raksha Bandhan brings with it a familiar warmth. A sister ties a thread on her brother’s wrist, and in return, he promises to always protect her.

In a world where the safety of women continues to be compromised every single day, relying solely on someone else’s protection is no longer enough. According to the National Crime Records Bureau (NCRB), more than 85 sexual harassment cases are reported daily in India. And these are just the official number what about the countless incidents that never make it to a police station?

The problem isn’t just the frequency of these crimes, it’s the mindset that allows them to happen. In most cases, the perpetrators don’t fear consequences.They walk freely, confident that they’ll get away with it, because the system rarely holds them accountable. That’s the most devastating part of it all.

This is why, while the sentiment behind Rakhi is heartwarming, it needs to evolve. A brother’s promise is powerful, but it shouldn’t be a woman’s only line of defense. True protection cannot just come from the outside, it has to come from within. From confidence. From awareness. From tools and systems that support you. From the unshakable belief that you have every right to feel safe in your body and in your surroundings.

At Impower, we believe in strengthening that feeling. We don’t want you to merely survive, we want you to thrive. To walk freely. To take up space unapologetically. We wish you never have to be in a situation where you must protect yourself. But if you are, we want you to feel equipped, aware, and supported.
.
So this Rakhi, while you promise to protect her also empower her.
Gift her the tools that can actually help her feel safe when you’re not around.
Gift her pepper spray. Gift her confidence. Gift her Impower.
.
#BuriNazarWaleTereMuhPeSpray #Rakshabandhan #Sibling #Rakhi #Impowerher #Sironahygiene

Hydrate yourself🚨
.
When you dehydrate yourself the color of the pee becomes dark because your body tries to conserve as much water as possible, causing less water to be released in your urine. 

The smell can also become stronger and more pungent due to the higher concentration of waste products like urea. 

You might notice that you pee less frequently as your body is holding onto water to maintain essential functions, which is a clear signal that you’re not drinking enough fluids. 
.
Chronic dehydration can lead to more serious health problems, so it’s crucial to stay hydrated.
.

Does It Hurt Less for Her or Is She Just Tougher?
.
Periods hurt because of chemicals called prostaglandins. These help your uterus tighten to shed its lining. Younger women usually have more prostaglandins and feel cramps more intensely—your uterus squeezes harder, making cramps, nausea, headaches and fatigue worse. As you get older or after having a baby, hormone levels change and your body gets better at handling the pain, so many moms experience less intense cramps 
.
Cramps shouldn’t control your life. Tap Shop Now to discover gentle period care products like soothing heat patches soft absorbent pads and calming supplements to support your comfort every month.

Ouch! Period boobs making every little bump feel like a big deal 😣 
.
Breast sensitivity is a common complaint among women during their menstrual cycle. 

The fluctuating hormone levels, primarily estrogen and progesterone, are the culprits behind this discomfort. As estrogen increases, breast tissue swells, leading to a feeling of fullness or tenderness. 

Additionally, progesterone causes the milk glands in the breasts to enlarge, contributing to the overall increase in breast size and sensitivity. 

While this is a normal bodily function, the discomfort can vary in intensity from mild to severe, significantly impacting a woman’s daily life.
.

Ever experienced this? 💀
.
While most people associate period cramps with lower abdominal pain, many also experience sharp, shooting pain in the butt or lower back and yes, it’s completely normal. 

This happens because of prostaglandins, hormone-like chemicals that are released to help the uterus contract and shed its lining. These contractions can radiate to nearby muscles and nerves, including the pelvic floor muscles and sciatic nerve, which extend into the lower back and buttocks. 

Additionally, some people experience constipation or bloating during their periods, which puts added pressure on the rectal area, intensifying the discomfort. 

So if you’ve ever found yourself frozen mid-step because of a sudden “butt cramp” during your period you’re definitely not alone, and your body isn’t malfunctioning, it’s just reacting to everything happening inside
.
